## About `config/credentials.json`

This file is **created automatically** by `first_login.py` after you complete
the 2FA flow. You should **never** create or edit it by hand.

⚠️ **This file is sensitive.** Anyone with it can access your Blink account,
view your cameras, and download your clips. The repo's `.gitignore` excludes
it. Never commit, share, paste, or upload this file.

If you ever need to reset it: delete the file and re-run `first_login.py`.

### What's inside

| Field | What it is | Set by |
|---|---|---|
| `username` | The email address you use to log into Blink. **You enter this** when running `first_login.py`. | You, at first login |
| `password` | Your Blink account password. **You enter this** when running `first_login.py`. Stored so `blinkpy` can refresh tokens automatically without re-prompting you. | You, at first login |
| `uid` | A unique identifier for *this copy* of the script (so Blink can tell our app apart from your phone, your tablet, etc.). | Auto-generated |
| `device_id` | The name our app reports to Blink. Always `"Blinkpy"` for this project. | Auto |
| `token` | Short-lived OAuth access token (~4 hour life). Used as the "password" for API calls. Refreshes automatically. | Blink's servers |
| `expires_in` | How long `token` is valid for, in seconds. Usually 14400 (4 hours). | Blink's servers |
| `expiration_date` | Unix timestamp (seconds since 1970) when `token` expires. | Blink's servers |
| `refresh_token` | Long-lived token used to mint a new `token` when the current one expires. This is why you don't have to re-do 2FA every 4 hours. | Blink's servers |
| `host` | Hostname of the Blink API server for your region. | Blink's servers |
| `region_id` | Region code (e.g., `u060` for US-East). | Blink's servers |
| `client_id` | Numeric ID Blink assigns to our app instance at first registration. | Blink's servers |
| `account_id` | Your Blink account number. | Blink's servers |
| `user_id` | Your Blink user number (usually same as `account_id`). | Blink's servers |
| `hardware_id` | A UUID that Blink uses to identify this specific install. Like a hardware fingerprint. Generated once and reused. | Auto-generated |

### Bottom line

You provide **`username`** and **`password`** when you first run
`first_login.py`. Everything else is filled in automatically by Blink's
servers and `blinkpy`. Just don't share the file.

